Name: Alex
Video_Title: DeMISTifying Electronic Nicotine Delivery Systems (ENDS) and Their Effects on Hormones (trimmed)
Description:
this is a short description of how vapes, e-cigs, and juuls, known as electronic nicotine delivery systems (ends), can affect the body through an imbalance of hormones, specifically dopamine and insulin. ends can be broken down into active ingredients, such as nicotine and flavoring, and filler ingredients, such as propylene glycol, glycerol, and preservatives like formaldehyde. filler ingredients have other effects on the body not covered by the video. the active ingredients and some filler ingredients are absorbed by the lungs and travel through the blood stream to the brain. in the brain, nicotine, one of the common active ingredients, increases dopamine production and release. additionally, some flavorings have been shown to increase dopamine production, even in the absence of nicotine. in the brain, dopamine functions in cognition and mood. it is normally released after satisfying activities and is the primary factor behind the addictive nature of nicotine. outside of the brain, dopamine has been shown to increase urination through a decrease in salt absorption in the kidneys. additionally, dopamine has been shown to mimic diabetes mellitus by decreasing insulin production in the pancreas. insulin functions by increasing the transport of sugar from the bloodstream into cells. from there, the sugar can be made into atp for energy. thus, nicotine and some flavorings in ends can cause deleterious effects in the body through significant hormone imbalance.

special thanks to daelyn doughty for filming and editing and to the alleluia community school for allowing me to film in their beautiful auditorium.
